{
  "answer": "**The chapter matching this description is Chapter 1 (the sole chapter) of the *Nārada Smṛti* (Nārada's Treatise on Legal Procedure), in its section on ordeals (20.6–20.48).**[^1]\n\nThis text names exactly these **five ordeals**: the balance (*dhaṭa*), fire (*agni*), water (*udaka*), poison (*viṣa*), and consecrated water or sacred libation (*kośa*).[^2] It provides their procedural details, including:\n\n- **Fire ordeal**: The accused, having fasted and wrapped seven Aśvattha leaves around his hands with thread, takes \"a ball of iron heated to fire, weighing fifty *palas*,\" and walks \"slowly for seven steps,\" each separated by circles spaced thirty-two finger-breadths (i.e., seven circles each of sixteen finger-breadths).[^3]\n- **Poison ordeal**: Seven grains (one-twentieth of a sixth of a *pala*, less an eighth) of poison \"from the Śṛṅga or Himavat mountains\" (i.e., Śārṅga poison from the Himalayan mountains), mixed with ghee.[^4]\n- **Sacred libation (consecrated water) ordeal**: The accused drinks it; he is pure unless \"any personal affliction... [occurs] within a week, or again within two weeks\" (i.e., no calamity within fourteen days).[^5]\n\nThe verse addressing the balance as **\"O Mother\"** (praying to be raised if pure, lowered if sinful) is:\n\n> You are called 'Balance' (*dhaṭa*) by words that are synonyms for *Dharma*. You know the sins and meritorious deeds of all beings. You alone, O Balance, know what mortals do not.[^6]\n\n[^1]: *Nārada Smṛti*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-983bae).\n[^2]: *Nārada Smṛti*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-6ade8c).\n[^3]: *Nārada Smṛti*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-e66264) (palas, leaves); [#p-867021](works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-867021) (circles).\n[^4]: *Nārada Smṛti*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-0d72c4).\n[^5]: *Nārada Smṛti*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-3dc05f).\n[^6]: *Nārada Smṛti*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-87395a).",
